<div id=3D"sbo-rt-content" style=3D"transform: none;"><div class=3D"annotat=
or-wrapper"><div class=3D"chap">
<h2 class=3D"chtitle"><a id=3D"h47"></a><a id=3D"page_177"></a><span class=
=3D"cn">6</span> NAILING THE INTERVIEW</h2>
</div>
<p class=3D"noindent">I suspect that many readers will have picked up this =
book because they are seeking a BA role for the first time, or perhaps they=
 are experienced practitioners who are considering their next move or promo=
tion. Equally, I suspect some readers will be BA managers considering how t=
o develop and nurture their team.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">This chapter focuses on the recruitment and selection=
 of business analysis candidates, and will be of particular use to those wh=
o are seeking their next BA role. It may also be of interest to BA managers=
 and those who are interested in considering a variety of approaches to rec=
ruitment and management. However, it is primarily written with the perspect=
ive of a candidate (rather than a recruiter) in mind.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">This chapter covers preparing a CV or r=C3=A9sum=C3=
=A9, searching the market and securing an interview, preparing for the inte=
rview, the day itself and following up. Practical tips are provided within =
each topic.</p>
<h3 class=3D"h3" id=3D"sec34"><a id=3D"h48"></a>PREPARING A CV OR R=C3=89SU=
M=C3=89</h3>
<p class=3D"noindent">In most situations, even if you are applying for a ne=
w role within your own organisation, it will be necessary for you to prepar=
e a curriculum vitae (CV) or r=C3=A9sum=C3=A9. The nature and format of thi=
s document will vary depending on the country and culture in which you are =
working, but some general tips are provided below which apply in most situa=
tions.</p>
<h4 class=3D"h4"><a id=3D"page_178"></a>Landing your first business analyst=
 role</h4>
<p class=3D"noindent">In many ways, the hardest CV to create is the one tha=
t will enable you to make a transition into a =E2=80=98pure=E2=80=99 BA rol=
e for the first time. Perhaps you have been working in an operational role =
and have decided that you want to take a different path. Or perhaps you hav=
e worked in a different project-centric role (such as a tester or PMO analy=
st) and have decided that analysis is a role that you are keen to transitio=
n into.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">In these situations, it is important to reflect on th=
e BA experience that you already have. Even if you have never had =E2=80=98=
business analyst=E2=80=99 as a job title, you may well have undertaken some=
 business analysis work. It will be important to draw upon this and pull ou=
t the experience on your CV. It can be extremely helpful to use industry-st=
andard terminology when you do this: for example, if you were involved in r=
unning workshops and interviews, you might explain that you =E2=80=98elicit=
ed initial requirements for a new web-based system using interviews and fac=
ilitated workshops=E2=80=99. To illustrate this point, <a href=3D"https://l=
earning.oreilly.com/library/view/business-analyst-/9781780174280/16_chapter=
06.xhtml#tab6-1">Table 6.1</a> considers two examples of roles that might s=
eem completely unrelated to business analysis (a call centre team leader an=
d a trainer).</p>
<div class=3D"border1"></div>
<p class=3D"captiont"><a id=3D"tab6-1"></a><span class=3D"cap"><span class=
=3D"bold">Table 6.1</span></span> <span class=3D"bold">Potential business a=
nalysis experience gained in other roles</span></p>
<p class=3D"image"><img src=3D"https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/bu=
siness-analyst-/9781780174280/images/tab6-1.jpg" alt=3D"" width=3D"1033" he=
ight=3D"517" data-mfp-src=3D"/library/view/business-analyst-/9781780174280/=
images/tab6-1.jpg"></p>
<p class=3D"image"><a id=3D"page_179"></a><img src=3D"https://learning.orei=
lly.com/library/view/business-analyst-/9781780174280/images/tab6-1a.jpg" al=
t=3D"" width=3D"1034" height=3D"1010" data-mfp-src=3D"/library/view/busines=
s-analyst-/9781780174280/images/tab6-1a.jpg"></p>
<p class=3D"noindent">As you can see from <a href=3D"https://learning.oreil=
ly.com/library/view/business-analyst-/9781780174280/16_chapter06.xhtml#tab6=
-1">Table 6.1</a>, even though these roles initially seem to be completely =
unrelated to business analysis, there are a number of examples of where ele=
ments of analysis have been carried out =E2=80=93 and, if we were to examin=
e things further, there would undoubtedly be even more examples of transfer=
rable skills. If your goal is to transition to a BA role, it can be valuabl=
e to make a similar table of your own experience. You might choose to use t=
he frameworks mentioned in <a href=3D"https://learning.oreilly.com/library/=
view/business-analyst-/9781780174280/14_chapter04.xhtml">Chapter 4</a>, per=
haps mapping your experience to stages on the BCS Business Analysis Process=
 Model or against <a id=3D"page_180"></a>IIBA<sup>=C2=AE</sup>=E2=80=99s Kn=
owledge Areas. It is equally (if not more) important to consider your inter=
personal skills as these will be crucial for the role =E2=80=93 and having =
examples of relevant experience will help you to stand out.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Make sure you can fully justify each example you prov=
ide, as it is likely that a skilled interviewer would ask questions in orde=
r to understand your experience further if you were to proceed to interview=
. Additionally, for each relevant piece of experience, it can be valuable t=
o briefly explain the outcome. Rather than explaining that you have facilit=
ation experience, you might explain how that helped the organisation or tea=
m with which you worked.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Certification can also help your CV to stand out. If =
you are embarking on your first BA role, considering a foundation or entry-=
level certificate (such as BCS=E2=80=99s Foundation Certificate in Business=
 Analysis or IIBA<sup>=C2=AE</sup>=E2=80=99s ECBA=E2=84=A2) could be a usef=
ul first step. This shows employers that you are serious about making a tra=
nsition and also shows that you have taken steps to gain business analysis =
knowledge.</p>
<h4 class=3D"h4">Apply your analytical skills to your career</h4>
<p class=3D"noindent">Searching for and applying for a BA role can be an ex=
cellent opportunity to practice some of your business analysis skills by ap=
plying them to your career. Initially, this might sound like a rather unusu=
al thing to say, but on further examination there is a lot of commonality b=
etween a career change and a change project within an organisation. For exa=
mple:</p>
<div class=3D"top">
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> There is an =E2=80=
=98as is=E2=80=99 (your current state of employment and a desire to move aw=
ay from this).</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> There is a longer-te=
rm vision, mission or strategy relating to your life and career goals.</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> There is a series of=
 =E2=80=98could be=E2=80=99 options (e.g. you could become a BA, or you mig=
ht choose another role such as tester or SME =E2=80=93 or perhaps something=
 completely different!).</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><a id=3D"page_181"></a><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</spa=
n> There is a chosen option which fits with your vision, mission or strateg=
y (which might be =E2=80=98to become a BA=E2=80=99).</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> There are many ways =
of getting to this goal (see <a href=3D"https://learning.oreilly.com/librar=
y/view/business-analyst-/9781780174280/16_chapter06.xhtml#fig6-1">Figure 6.=
1</a>), and you will have a range of strengths to draw on but also weakness=
es to address.</p>
</div>
<div class=3D"border1"></div>
<p class=3D"captionf"><a id=3D"fig6-1"></a><span class=3D"cap"><span class=
=3D"bold">Figure 6.1</span></span> <span class=3D"bold">There are many rout=
es to becoming a BA</span></p>
<p class=3D"image"><img src=3D"https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/bu=
siness-analyst-/9781780174280/images/fig6-1.jpg" alt=3D"" width=3D"863" hei=
ght=3D"339" data-mfp-src=3D"/library/view/business-analyst-/9781780174280/i=
mages/fig6-1.jpg"></p>
<p class=3D"noindent">When searching for and applying for a BA role is conc=
eptualised in this way, it is clear that there is a whole range of business=
 analysis techniques that can help. For example, it can be very useful to l=
ook at the types of BA role that you are aiming for (<a href=3D"https://lea=
rning.oreilly.com/library/view/business-analyst-/9781780174280/12_chapter02=
.xhtml">Chapter 2</a> may help with this) and benchmark yourself against th=
em. What skills do you excel at? What are you lacking? This requires brutal=
 honesty, and it can often be very worthwhile to discuss your assessment of=
 yourself with a trusted colleague and solicit feedback from them. Colleagu=
es are often very good at pointing out strengths that we don=E2=80=99t even=
 know about =E2=80=93 but also weaknesses that fall within our blind spots.=
 This can be a useful first step in carrying out a SWOT analysis.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">In considering your strengths and weaknesses, you cou=
ld also consider what other resources you have access to which might help y=
ou in your journey towards becoming a BA. If you work for an organisation t=
hat employs BAs, could you shadow a BA for a period of time? Could you appl=
y for a secondment, or engineer a situation where you work part time on a p=
roject to strengthen your analytical skills and mindset? If your organisati=
on does not have BAs, perhaps there is the opportunity to slowly show the v=
alue of the role and advocate <a id=3D"page_182"></a>for its creation. If y=
ou do so, you will be a perfectly placed candidate for the role itself.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">As well as identifying strengths and weaknesses, it i=
s also valuable to consider what opportunities are open to you and what thr=
eats exist. BA techniques such as PESTLE and STEEPLE can be helpful here to=
 consider what factors, outside the scope of your immediate job, might be r=
elevant. For further discussion of these and other techniques in a broader =
context, please see the references at the back of this book, such as the BC=
S book <span class=3D"italic">Business Analysis</span> (Paul, Cadle and Yea=
tes 2014) and IIBA<sup>=C2=AE</sup>=E2=80=99s <span class=3D"italic">Guide =
to the Business Analysis Body of Knowledge</span> (International Institute =
of Business Analysis 2015).</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Having established your strengths, weaknesses, opport=
unities and threats, a useful step can be to decide which opportunities you=
 are going to pursue. You can decide how you will use your strengths to max=
imise those opportunities, and also build a strategy to address any relevan=
t weaknesses and protect against any significant threats.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">The use of analysis techniques can continue throughou=
t your job-searching process (and, ultimately, can also be used as you mana=
ge your career). It can help you to build a roadmap to the job you desire, =
addressing how you will gain any necessary experience or plug any relevant =
skills gaps. Once you have decided which direction you wish to take, you ca=
n use options analysis to determine how to get there. For example, if you a=
ssess that you have a weakness in requirements elicitation, you might under=
take some formal training, or you might seek support from a colleague. Equa=
lly, you might self-study and try to put what you learn into practice as so=
on as possible. Each of these routes has costs and benefits associated with=
 them, and you could carry out a very informal and lightweight cost=E2=80=
=93benefit analysis of each approach (of course, you are unlikely to want t=
o go into lengthy detail =E2=80=93 but using an analysis mindset to weigh u=
p the options is very important).</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">A similar mindset can be applied to the jobs that you=
 choose to apply for, or you can put it to use if you need to choose betwee=
n <a id=3D"page_183"></a>multiple job offers. It is likely that there will =
be pros and cons of each job and employer. You can refer back to your visio=
n, mission or strategy and ask =E2=80=98Which job would get me closest to w=
hat I want to achieve?=E2=80=99 It is also important to ask not just what y=
ou will gain from each job but also what you will need to give up. For exam=
ple, you might choose a job which involves a longer commute (so you lose ti=
me at home) in order to gain a foot in the door with an employer that you r=
eally want to work for. Knowing what you value is vital.</p>
<h4 class=3D"h4">Showing a growth mindset</h4>
<p class=3D"noindent">When conducting research for this book, I interviewed=
 a number of BA managers. One theme that particularly resonated was that su=
ccessful BAs tend to possess a growth mindset, and really own their own car=
eer:</p>
<div class=3D"blockquote">
<p class=3D"noindent">One of the primary things I look for when recruiting =
BAs is whether the candidate=E2=80=99s CV demonstrates a growth mindset. I =
am a firm believer that we are all responsible for our <span class=3D"itali=
c">own</span> careers, and, whatever a candidate=E2=80=99s background, I lo=
ok for evidence of professional and personal development. (Craig Rollason, =
Business Analysis and Solution Architecture Manager, National Grid)</p>
</div>
<p class=3D"noindent">A practitioner of business analysis will need to cont=
inually develop throughout their career. It is important to stay current wi=
th relevant business, industry and technological trends =E2=80=93 and the a=
bility to learn quickly can be crucial. A senior BA may be parachuted into =
a business or industry they have not worked in before, and will need to ver=
y quickly assemble the information they need. Whilst a junior BA will norma=
lly benefit from much more support and guidance, there is still the need to=
 demonstrate curiosity and a growth mindset.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Therefore, at every stage of your career it is import=
ant to use your CV to showcase <span class=3D"bold">how</span> you have dev=
eloped. This might be through formal training, self-study or deliberate exp=
osure to projects and assignments that have helped you to gain an <a id=3D"=
page_184"></a>additional breadth or depth of experience. It could even be t=
hrough engaging with professional associations and forums =E2=80=93 perhaps=
 attending BCS or IIBA<sup>=C2=AE</sup> events, or attending or speaking at=
 BA conferences.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">It is also very valuable to highlight opportunities w=
here you have given back or contributed to the BA community =E2=80=93 wheth=
er that is inside or outside your organisation. If you are a senior BA, per=
haps you have mentored others. This is very useful for a potential employer=
 to know, as it shows that you are interested not just in your own career d=
evelopment but also in that of others. Alternatively, you may have voluntee=
red for a BA community initiative, written a blog post or white paper, or c=
arried out some other type of voluntary initiative that has benefited other=
 BAs or the wider BA community. If so, ensure this is showcased on your CV.=
</p>
<h4 class=3D"h4">General considerations</h4>
<p class=3D"noindent">Whether you are an experienced or new BA, there are a=
 number of general considerations that it is worth keeping in mind. Firstly=
, it is important to <span class=3D"bold">tailor your CV</span> to the role=
 that you are applying for. Remember, the recruiter or hiring manager is li=
kely to see a large volume of CVs, and initially your aim is to get past th=
e =E2=80=98first sift=E2=80=99.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Find out as much about the role as you can in advance=
 by thoroughly reading the job description and gaining any other general in=
dustry insight. For example, if you know that the organisation is seeking B=
As with data migration experience, then be sure to clearly signpost the exp=
erience you have had working on projects that involve migration of data. Pi=
n down the techniques you have employed, and use your CV as an opportunity =
to show the positive outcomes that you and your colleagues were able to ach=
ieve.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Most jobs will have a published job description and p=
erhaps also a person specification. These documents are incredibly useful. =
Use these to tailor your CV =E2=80=93 this could be considered as a type of=
 mapping exercise. The more of the hiring <a id=3D"page_185"></a>manager=E2=
=80=99s requirements that you can confidently satisfy, the more likely you =
are to get an interview (and ultimately the job itself too).</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Finally, there is the contentious issue of CV length.=
 Views over the length of a CV vary significantly between organisations, in=
dustries and cultures =E2=80=93 and it is probably true (in the UK at least=
) that recruiting managers generally expect slightly longer CVs from BA can=
didates compared with some other disciplines, as they are keen to see a his=
tory of project experience. Yet, a general guide is that <span class=3D"bol=
d">brevity with precision</span> is highly likely to be appreciated by hiri=
ng managers. If you can keep your CV concise yet precise, signposting the k=
ey skills that are most relevant to the role you are applying for, this is =
likely to stand you in good stead.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Alongside your CV, it is also well worth considering =
your <span class=3D"bold">online presence</span>. What will an employer fin=
d if they search for you online? Do you have a strong presence on business =
networking sites? Have you ensured that any personal social media profiles =
are marked as private? Certainly, most candidates wouldn=E2=80=99t want a p=
otential employer seeing their holiday snaps! Conversely, an employer who s=
earches online for a candidate and finds a professional networking profile =
that aligns with their CV, along with links to articles that the candidate =
has written (or other relevant contributions to the BA community), will fee=
l a significant amount of confidence, particularly when they are considerin=
g a more senior role.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">There are many other considerations too which fall ou=
tside the scope of this book, but suffice to say that it is always worth ge=
tting a second (and third) pair of eyes on your CV. Consider getting truste=
d colleagues to <span class=3D"bold">peer-review</span> the document and pr=
ovide feedback with what jumped out at them and what they would suggest tha=
t you change. When arranging this type of peer review, it is important to p=
rovide the reviewer with details of the job you are applying for. That way,=
 they can point out any areas of the job description or person specificatio=
n that you have not covered.</p>
<h3 class=3D"h3" id=3D"sec35"><a id=3D"h49"></a><a id=3D"page_186"></a>SEAR=
CHING THE MARKET AND SECURING AN INTERVIEW</h3>
<p class=3D"noindent">Often this step takes place in parallel with the prep=
aration and tailoring of a CV. Here, it is necessary to proactively identif=
y relevant roles for which you want to apply. If you are already employed a=
nd enjoy working for your company, then one option may be to seek a transfe=
r (or promotion) to a BA role <span class=3D"bold">within your own organisa=
tion</span>. If you are seeking your first BA role, this is often a very vi=
able option. You will be a =E2=80=98known candidate=E2=80=99, and often a h=
iring manager will give an internal candidate a chance in a way that they m=
ight not for an equivalent external candidate seeking their first BA role. =
The internal candidate will have knowledge of the organisation, its culture=
 and its stakeholder landscape. Even though they might not (yet) have a ful=
l repertoire of BA experience, their business and domain knowledge will pro=
vide them with a springboard to develop from. An external candidate will no=
t have this background knowledge and may therefore be disadvantaged.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">If you are seeking a role <span class=3D"bold">outsid=
e</span> <span class=3D"bold">your organisation</span> =E2=80=93 perhaps yo=
ur next (more senior) BA role =E2=80=93 then there are a number of routes. =
Firstly, do not underestimate the power of your network. It is likely that =
you have met lots of skilled BAs, particularly if you have attended trainin=
g courses, conferences and other events. You may also know previous colleag=
ues who have moved to other organisations. A few tentative discussions over=
 coffee with your trusted network can often uncover roles that are advertis=
ed in places you haven=E2=80=99t yet looked.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">It is worth taking a focused approach, as illustrated=
 by the following quote:</p>
<div class=3D"blockquote">
<p class=3D"noindent">Don=E2=80=99t take a scattergun approach when applyin=
g for jobs =E2=80=93 focus on the ones that you really want. Remember, you =
<span class=3D"italic">choose</span> which companies to apply for. Choose t=
he right organisation =E2=80=93 one that has the right level of structure a=
nd right ethos for you. (Michelle Shakesheff, Business Analysis Manager, Zu=
rich Insurance)</p>
</div>
<p class=3D"noindent"><a id=3D"page_187"></a>If there is a particular compa=
ny that you are keen to work for, then it is well worth keeping an eye on i=
ts recruitment website. However, increasingly it seems (in the UK at least)=
 that many BA roles are filled using the skills of specialist recruiters. T=
his is true for both permanent and contract staff, and it should be noted t=
hat, generally speaking, in the UK, contract resource allocation is almost =
always conducted via an agency.</p>
<h4 class=3D"h4">Working with an agency</h4>
<p class=3D"noindent">A search on social media will find that there are a w=
ide range of views on the effectiveness and usefulness of recruitment consu=
ltancies, as illustrated in the quote below. Yet, a good recruitment consul=
tant can often help you to find opportunities that you might not otherwise =
have been aware of. Indeed, a good specialist recruiter will often have an =
extremely wide network in a whole range of companies and industries, and ma=
y be well placed to represent you as you move towards your next role. Many =
recruiters will give feedback on your CV too =E2=80=93 after all, it is in =
their interests for you to get the role!</p>
<div class=3D"blockquote">
<p class=3D"noindent">Recruiters can be great, but unfortunately I have see=
n some behaviour I consider to be unethical. I was once =E2=80=98represente=
d=E2=80=99 by a recruiter when trying to get a job for a company I really w=
anted to work for. He disappeared and didn=E2=80=99t return my calls. I fou=
nd out months later that his firm was apparently not authorised to recruit =
for the client firm; he had presumably heard about a vacancy and was sendin=
g my CV to the company =E2=80=98speculatively=E2=80=99. I did eventually ge=
t a job there, only after speaking with the =E2=80=98official=E2=80=99 pref=
erred recruitment partner. But, if you do your research, there are some ver=
y good recruiters out there too. Once you find a good recruiter, stay in to=
uch, and recommend them to others! (Anonymous BA who previously worked in f=
inancial services)</p>
</div>
<p class=3D"noindent">Lawrence Darvill, Chair of the BA Manager Forum and D=
irector at AssistKD, who previously worked as a specialist BA recruiter, of=
fers the following practical pieces of advice:</p>
<div class=3D"blockquote">
<p class=3D"noindent"><a id=3D"page_188"></a>Build up relationships with re=
cruiters and be sure to take recommendations from colleagues and friends to=
 determine which recruiters are genuine and trustworthy. When working with =
a recruiter, don=E2=80=99t be afraid to ask questions. As a minimum, consid=
er asking:</p>
</div>
<div class=3D"top">
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> Can you please send =
through a full role profile?</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> What are the essenti=
al requirements for the role?</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> Please confirm the c=
lient name and specific location.</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> How long has the rol=
e been live?</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> Please confirm in wr=
iting if you submit my CV.</p>
</div>
<p class=3D"noindent">Probably the most important factor which is highlight=
ed in Lawrence=E2=80=99s advice is the importance of drawing on the experie=
nce of your network and finding out the names of the firms and individual r=
ecruitment consultants whom your contacts have found to be effective in the=
 past.</p>
<h3 class=3D"h3" id=3D"sec36"><a id=3D"h50"></a>PREPARING FOR THE INTERVIEW=
</h3>
<p class=3D"noindent">If an employer likes the look of your polished and fo=
cused CV, the next stage will normally be for them to invite you for interv=
iew. The types of interview that organisations conduct vary significantly b=
ut include:</p>
<div class=3D"top">
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> initial telephone in=
terviews, often used to screen and shortlist candidates;</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> face-to-face capabil=
ity-based interviews;</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> face-to-face intervi=
ews with scenarios, where you are given a case study and asked how you woul=
d approach the situation;</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> psychometric or simi=
lar tests;</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> assessment days, oft=
en consisting of a range of the approaches mentioned above.</p>
</div>
<p class=3D"noindent"><a id=3D"page_189"></a>This list is by no means exhau=
stive, and when you accept an interview it is well worth asking what type i=
t will be and whether there is any information that can be shared with you =
in advance. Some organisations might, for example, provide details of the s=
tructure of the BA team, which will be extremely useful when you are prepar=
ing.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">A general rule for preparing for an interview is to t=
hink like an employer. Imagine you were on the other side of the interview =
table. What would you be looking for? What doubts might you have and what q=
uestions might you ask?</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">This can be a good time to reflect back on the SWOT a=
nalysis mentioned earlier. A good interviewer will probe and understand you=
r strengths and weaknesses, so it can be valuable to consider whether any o=
f the weaknesses might be of particular concern. Yet, it is important not t=
o blow them out of proportion =E2=80=93 an employer may be willing to overl=
ook something that you view as a major weakness, particularly if you have s=
ignificant strengths in other areas. Indeed, self-awareness and the ability=
 to see one=E2=80=99s own weaknesses are often viewed very favourably.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Preparing for an interview can also be an opportunity=
 to deploy other types of analytical skill =E2=80=93 for example, your rese=
arch skills. It is standard advice to research the company that you are bei=
ng interviewed by. Yet, as a BA, it is valuable to do so with even greater =
rigour. Potentially useful sources include:</p>
<div class=3D"top">
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> <span class=3D"bold"=
>Company annual reports:</span> These will often give a sense of the compan=
y=E2=80=99s strategic direction, the opportunities and threats that are in =
its sights, and how it intends to respond to them. They also give a useful =
view into the finances of the company (e.g. are they growing or contracting=
?), which might give you an insight into the types of projects being run. L=
arger companies will typically produce lengthy annual reports which also st=
ate the organisation=E2=80=99s mission and vision.</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> <span class=3D"bold"=
>Company website:</span> This is the public face of the organisation. It wi=
ll typically tell you a lot about what <a id=3D"page_190"></a>the organisat=
ion does and its core product lines<span class=3D"italic">.</span> The webs=
ite will often help you to understand how the organisation positions its se=
rvices compared with its competitors, which can help you to determine likel=
y sources of competitive advantage. For example, you may be able to determi=
ne that the organisation is promoting itself as low cost, or perhaps it is =
instead selling the higher quality of its goods or services, and so forth.<=
/p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> <span class=3D"bold"=
>News articles:</span> Searching a news archive on the internet can be an e=
xtremely good way of gaining additional insight. Often you will find press =
releases that provide information about news from the company=E2=80=99s per=
spective =E2=80=93 but there may also be other articles (and, in the case o=
f publicly listed companies, market analysis) which provide information abo=
ut the company=E2=80=99s direction and the external factors that are affect=
ing it.</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> <span class=3D"bold"=
>Social media:</span> It can be very illuminating to see not only what the =
company itself is saying on social media but also how much it engages with =
such channels. It is also valuable to see what others are saying about the =
company. Of course, social media is filled with opinions, so assertions fro=
m those outside the organisation should be treated carefully.</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> <span class=3D"bold"=
>Your network:</span> People within your professional network can often pro=
vide very useful insights too. If you know somebody who works at (or used t=
o work at) the company, they may be able to give you an inside view of how =
the organisation operates. They might be able to tell you about the particu=
lar types of challenges that the organisation faces, the maturity and recog=
nition of the BA function, and so forth.</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> <span class=3D"bold"=
>Conference and event notes:</span> If you have been to previous conference=
s or BA events, it is well worth looking back at your notes to see whether =
anyone from the organisation presented. If you still have copies of the pro=
ceedings, looking at the slides may yield a further flavour of the organisa=
tion=E2=80=99s set-up.</p>
</div>
<p class=3D"noindent"><a id=3D"page_191"></a>Another general resource is, o=
f course, the internet. An internet search for the company=E2=80=99s name w=
ill undoubtedly uncover a wide range of documents and links. However, a wor=
d of warning here: it is very tempting to try to find shortcuts<span class=
=3D"italic">.</span> Be very wary of sites that offer you practice BA inter=
view questions. Whilst these sites certainly have their uses (and some of t=
hem are run by extremely experienced and well-known BAs), it is probably fa=
ir to say that there is no such thing as a =E2=80=98typical=E2=80=99 BA int=
erview question. By all means, take a look, but remember that the type of q=
uestions you will be asked will depend a lot on the role, the job descripti=
on, the type of project and the format of the interview. You would not want=
 to lull yourself into a false sense of security!</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">In fact, one very effective way to prepare for an int=
erview, if you have the time, is to find a friendly colleague or contact wh=
o knows enough about business analysis and is prepared to help you by condu=
cting a mock interview. This normally works best when you give the mock int=
erviewer as much information about the company and the position as you can =
=E2=80=93 crucially, it is important that they see the job description and =
person specification so that they can prepare relevant questions. You shoul=
d give them this information, along with a copy of your CV, well in advance=
 so that they can prepare. You should be careful to ask them to give you an=
 interview for the job you are applying for rather than a generic mock inte=
rview. Ask them to put themselves in the shoes of the hiring manager and im=
agine the types of question the manager would ask. Explain to them that you=
 value their honest opinion, and suggest that you discuss feedback and idea=
s for improvement immediately after (not during) the mock interview.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">This approach is particularly effective when the mock=
 interviewer is someone with recruitment and interviewing experience, and i=
t can be even more effective if it is someone you do not know well (perhaps=
 a colleague of a colleague). However, it will be beneficial even with a fr=
iend or close colleague, providing they feel comfortable giving honest and =
blunt feedback.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent"><a id=3D"page_192"></a>Of course, soliciting feedback=
 from your interviewer can be tricky if they are someone you know well. The=
refore, when you begin, it is worth explaining that you will receive all fe=
edback in the spirit it is given and that you are interested in <span class=
=3D"bold">all</span> feedback, whether it is indicative of a strength, a we=
akness or even just a gut feeling that something could be improved. Jot dow=
n any feedback, ask further questions where needed, and once the interviewe=
r has finished giving feedback thank them and ask that they drop you an ema=
il if any other feedback springs to mind. Often, very useful ideas crop up =
a few minutes after a meeting ends, so it is well worth catering for this t=
oo.</p>
<h3 class=3D"h3" id=3D"sec37"><a id=3D"h51"></a>THE DAY ITSELF</h3>
<p class=3D"noindent">When the day comes, providing you have prepared well,=
 things ought to go relatively smoothly. In fact, the types of general tips=
 and advice that would be given for any interview are relevant here. It is =
worth pointing out that there are many sources of general interview advice.=
 If you have not been to an interview for a while, you may want to tap into=
 your network for their thoughts, and also take stock of some of the genera=
l resources that are out there on the internet. This section covers some of=
 the most pertinent points.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Firstly, as you would with any important meeting, it =
is worth ensuring that you have considered which travel options are best an=
d have planned for delays. Arriving early is best =E2=80=93 it is better to=
 arrive an hour early and find a nearby caf=C3=A9 to complete some final pr=
eparation than to risk hitting the rush-hour traffic and arriving just abou=
t on time but stressed, or late!</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">There is a point of debate around what to wear for a =
BA interview. Increasingly, organisations are moving towards a dress-down c=
ulture. However, unless you are sure the interviewees are expecting you to =
dress down, it is normally safer to dress up more formally for an interview=
.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Be sure that you carry any relevant documentation tha=
t is required. If you have been asked to prepare a presentation, ask <a id=
=3D"page_193"></a>in advance whether you will be presenting it with or with=
out slides, and whether you should bring printed handouts. Additionally, al=
though the interviewers will normally have a copy of your CV to hand, there=
 is no harm in carrying a few spares just in case they have left them at th=
eir desk.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Although you will undoubtedly be nervous towards the =
start, it is likely that you will relax as the interview continues. Most em=
ployers look favourably on candidates who engage and ask questions, so do f=
eel able to interject either for clarification or to seek further informati=
on. This is particularly relevant for a BA role, as the hiring manager is g=
oing to be looking for someone who can actively elicit requirements, ideas =
and responses from stakeholders and engage with them. Use the interview to =
talk about your experiences but also to showcase your interpersonal skills.=
 Don=E2=80=99t be afraid of saying what did not work well =E2=80=93 this ty=
pe of reflection (providing it is accompanied by learning) is often viewed =
very positively. Some interviewers may also perceive it as a sign of an aut=
hentic candidate: very few people in the world have had every activity and =
project go exactly as they planned. Explaining what went wrong, what you wo=
uld do differently and how the experience improved your skills as a practit=
ioner can be an effective way of conveying the ability to be a reflective p=
ractitioner.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">As well as interjecting with relevant questions throu=
ghout the interview, it is normal practice for there to be a section reserv=
ed at the very end for any specific questions that you may have. It is wort=
h keeping your BA hat on for this. You might ask questions about the bigges=
t change that the organisation is facing and how this is affecting projects=
. Or you might ask about the structure of the BA team, the types of project=
s that it is involved with and the techniques that it is using. This is a r=
eal opportunity to find out more about the organisation, the BA team and so=
 on. It is not normally a good time to ask about pay, benefits and so on (t=
hese types of questions are best handled separately, outside the interview)=
. At the end of the interview, there will normally be an opportunity to tha=
nk the interviewers for their time and ask what the next steps will be.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent"><a id=3D"page_194"></a>Of course, the summation above=
 is based on somewhat of a typical interview structure. It may be that you =
are asked to give a presentation, respond to a scenario or attend a longer =
selection day. In most cases, the advice above will still be valid =E2=80=
=93 although the nature of the activities within the interview may vary. Ho=
wever, there is one final point worth noting: it probably goes without sayi=
ng, but remember that your interview starts long before you enter the inter=
view room. The way that you respond to emails, the way that you appear when=
 you are waiting in reception and so forth can all affect how an interviewe=
r or recruiter warms (or does not warm) to you. This can be particularly pe=
rtinent for candidates attending =E2=80=98selection centres=E2=80=99 with s=
essions that may last several hours or even a whole day. If (for example) y=
ou take part in a selection centre day that spans lunch, you might find tha=
t you are offered a buffet lunch with other candidates. Remember that =E2=
=80=93 either consciously or unconsciously =E2=80=93 the way that you act d=
uring lunch may contribute (to some extent) towards your success. Imagine b=
eing a hiring manager who has to choose between two strong candidates where=
 there is no easy way to distinguish between them. Yet, at lunch, one candi=
date chatted and asked questions, and the other retired to a corner and did=
 not interact. All other things being equal, it would probably be the more =
proactively social candidate who would get the role.</p>
<h3 class=3D"h3" id=3D"sec38"><a id=3D"h52"></a>FOLLOWING UP</h3>
<p class=3D"noindent">Many recruiters will get back to candidates promptly =
to provide them with feedback and to let them know about the hiring decisio=
n that has been made. Unfortunately, though, experience shows that sometime=
s candidates need to chase for feedback =E2=80=93 particularly if they were=
 unsuccessful. Whilst this can feel like a real chore (=E2=80=98I didn=E2=
=80=99t get the job =E2=80=93 why do I want to spend so much time pursuing =
it?=E2=80=99), it is worth remembering that the feedback you gain from this=
 interview might help you with the next. It has even been known for hiring =
managers to say, =E2=80=98The candidate wasn=E2=80=99t right for that role,=
 but we=E2=80=99d be very interested in seeing them apply for a different r=
ole.=E2=80=99</p>
<p class=3D"noindent"><a id=3D"page_195"></a>Of course, when you are succes=
sful, the follow-up is normally easier =E2=80=93 and might involve confirma=
tion of (or further negotiation) on pay and conditions, along with formalit=
ies such as signing paperwork and agreeing start dates. Incidentally, altho=
ugh it is not commonly done, it could be enlightening to ask for feedback f=
rom interviews where you were successful too. After all, wouldn=E2=80=99t i=
t be useful going into a job knowing what your new employers really like ab=
out you (and also the areas where they might be expecting you to develop)?<=
/p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Good luck!</p>
<h3 class=3D"h3" id=3D"sec39"><a id=3D"h53"></a>SUMMARY</h3>
<p class=3D"noindent">This chapter has provided some general advice on how =
to obtain your first (or your next) BA role. It gave advice on preparing a =
CV, including the suggestion to apply your analytical skills to your own ca=
reer and show a growth mindset. It discussed suggestions for searching the =
market and securing an interview, along with hints on how to prepare for an=
 interview. Finally, it offered brief suggestions on the day itself and how=
 to follow up after an interview.</p>
